VCamdroid iOS Support: Definitive Implementation Plan
Guiding Principles (Non-Negotiable)
Zero-copy pipeline or nothing. Every frame stays on the GPU from capture to encode. If a filter can't run on Metal/Core Image, it doesn't ship.
Custom TCP, not RTSP. Length-prefixed H.264 NAL units over raw TCP. The existing RTSP path stays for Android; iOS gets its own optimized path.
Virtual triple camera only. No lens "switching." The user sees a zoom slider, Apple handles the lens transitions seamlessly underneath.
No feature ships half-baked. Each phase produces a fully functional, shippable milestone.
Architecture: iOS Side
AVCaptureSession (.builtInTripleCamera)
    │
    ▼
AVCaptureVideoDataOutput (CMSampleBuffer, YUV 420v)
    │
    ├──► [Optional] Metal/Core Image GPU filter pipeline
    │
    ▼
CVPixelBuffer (NEVER leaves GPU memory)
    │
    ▼
VTCompressionSession (H.264, low-latency rate control, real-time)
    │
    ▼
CMBlockBuffer → Extract NAL units
    │
    ▼
TCP Server (length-prefix framing)
    │
    ├── Port A: Video stream (raw H.264 NAL units)
    └── Port B: Control channel (same binary protocol as Android)
Critical detail: The AVCaptureVideoDataOutput delivers CMSampleBuffer containing a CVPixelBuffer backed by an IOSurface. When you pass this directly to VTCompressionSession via VTCompressionSessionEncodeFrame, the encoder reads from the same GPU memory. Zero copies. The CPU never touches pixel data.

