Phase Order (4 Phases)
Phase 1: The Pipeline (Get pixels from iPhone to Windows)
This is the hardest phase. Everything else is layering controls on top.

iOS App:

CameraManager.swift - AVCaptureSession with .builtInWideAngleCamera (just the main lens to start)
H264Encoder.swift - VTCompressionSession wrapper, zero-copy, low-latency rate control
StreamServer.swift - TCP server, length-prefix framing: [4-byte uint32 length][NAL unit bytes]
ControlChannel.swift - TCP server on separate port, receives command bytes, same PacketType constants
DeviceDescriptor.swift - Serializes device info in the same binary format the Windows client expects, with a new deviceType field
StreamViewController.swift - Foreground camera preview, keep-screen-alive
Windows Client:

device_bridge.h / usbmux_bridge.cpp - Link against libusbmuxd, enumerate iOS devices, tunnel TCP ports
tcp_stream_receiver.h/.cpp - Read length-prefixed NAL units, feed to avcodec_send_packet / avcodec_receive_frame
DeviceDescriptor - Add deviceType field, parse iOS extended capabilities
Manager - Route iOS devices to TCPStreamReceiver, Android devices to RTSP::Receiver
Milestone: Plug iPhone in via USB, launch iOS app, see the camera feed in the Windows client preview and in OBS via the virtual webcam.

