TCP Stream Protocol Specification
This is the protocol the iOS app will use instead of RTSP:

Video Stream (Port 8554):
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ [4 bytes: uint32_t NAL length, big-endian]   │
│ [N bytes: raw H.264 NAL unit]                │
│ [4 bytes: uint32_t NAL length, big-endian]   │
│ [N bytes: raw H.264 NAL unit]                │
│ ...                                          │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────┘
First message after connection (before NAL units):
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ [4 bytes: magic 0x56434D44 ("VCMD")]         │
│ [1 byte: stream version (0x01)]              │
│ [1 byte: codec (0x01=H.264, 0x02=H.265)]    │
│ [2 bytes: uint16_t width, big-endian]        │
│ [2 bytes: uint16_t height, big-endian]       │
│ [1 byte: fps]                                │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────┘
Control Channel (Port 6969):
Same binary command protocol as Android.
Same PacketType byte constants.
Extended with new iOS-specific commands starting at 0x20:
  0x20: LENS_ZOOM      [4 bytes: float zoom factor]
  0x21: EXPOSURE        [4 bytes: float duration] [4 bytes: float ISO]
  0x22: WHITE_BALANCE   [4 bytes: float temp] [4 bytes: float tint]
  0x23: STUDIO_MODE     [1 byte: enabled]
Using the same control port (6969) and same command structure means the Windows Server class, Connection class, and the entire TCP infrastructure remain completely unchanged. Only the Manager command handler grows.

Key Technical Decisions (Why)
Decision	Why
Custom TCP over RTSP
Eliminates ~5-15ms of RTP/RTSP overhead. One less layer of packetization, no SDP negotiation, no RTP sequence tracking.
YUV 420v pixel format throughout
This is what the camera sensor produces and what VideoToolbox expects. Converting to BGRA (as some apps do) wastes 30-40% of encoding CPU time.
Big-endian wire format
Matches the existing Android protocol (ByteBuffer defaults to big-endian). Consistency across platforms.
Same port numbers (6969/8554)
The Windows client already opens these. The device bridge just changes how traffic reaches them (ADB tunnel vs usbmuxd tunnel).
.builtInTripleCamera only
Individual camera selection (.builtInTelephotoCamera) causes session restarts and frame drops. The virtual device provides seamless zoom with zero interruption.
Bonjour over QR codes for iOS
iPhones can't scan QR codes while simultaneously streaming camera. Bonjour is automatic and requires zero user interaction.
libusbmuxd (C library) over iproxy
Embedding the library directly into the Windows C++ client means no external process to manage, no race conditions, no "is iproxy running?" state tracking.
What You Need Before Starting
Mac with Xcode - confirmed
iTunes or Apple Devices app on your Windows PC - installs Apple Mobile Device Service (required for USB tunneling)
vcpkg addition: libusbmuxd and libimobiledevice for the Windows build
iOS deployment target: iOS 16.0+ (covers iPhone 16 Pro, drops ancient devices you don't care about)
This plan is ready to execute. When you want to start building, switch to Agent mode and I'll begin with Phase 1 - the core pipeline. I'd recommend starting with the iOS app since it's the greenfield component, then wiring up the Windows changes to receive from it.

